On this common $\eta$ scale the logit and probit curves are **not** identical: the probit (normal CDF) curve is **steeper** through the center, so the two differ most near $|\eta| \approx 1$ (e.g., $\Lambda(1) = 0.73$ vs $\Phi(1) = 0.84$) and converge only in the far tails, where both approach 0 and 1. They line up almost exactly once one linear predictor is rescaled by the $\approx 1.6$--$1.8$ factor (which is why probit coefficients are smaller in magnitude). The **complementary log-log (cloglog)** curve is asymmetric: it approaches 0 more gradually (left tail) but approaches 1 more rapidly (right tail). The cloglog link is used when the probability of the event changes more rapidly at higher values of the predictor (e.g., in survival analysis or dose-response studies). For most applications in education and social science, the logit and probit links are sufficient.

